---
title: Squash Agnolotti with Bacon & Scallops in a Brown Butter-Sage Cream Sauce
description: A fun Italian culinary lesson: Agnolotti and ravioli are both a type of stuffed pasta, but the way they’re prepared is what makes all the difference. Ravioli are made up of 2 separate thick pieces of pasta with the stuffing in the middle. Agnolotti are made by folding a single strip of pasta over the filling. Tonight’s pasta filling: creamy butternut squash. The agnolotti are cooked in a brown butter–sage cream sauce, then tossed with bacon and scallops for even more oomph. Now you’re ready to go off and teach all your friends what makes agnolotti so special, followed by a delicious helping of these pasta pockets.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/61e6f67a5cf31c11212db695-ac40413a.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/squash-agnolotti-with-bacon-scallops-61e6f67a5cf31c11212db695-616c3a9f.pdf
course: main course
cuisine: North America
author: Sara Heilman
nutrition:
  calories: 1040 kcal
  fat: 66 g
  saturated fat: 31 g
  carbohydrates: 65 g
  sugar: 15 g
  protein: 42 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 1780 mg
servings: 2
time required: 30 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/squash-agnolotti-with-bacon-and-scallops-61e6f67a5cf31c11212db695
---

Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil.

Wash and dry produce.

Heat a large, dry pan over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook, turning
occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy,
~{6-10%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Once cool enough to
handle, roughly chop. Carefully discard all but 1 TBSP bacon fat from pan (you'll
use this to cook the scallops in step 4).

While bacon cooks, zest and quarter @lemon{1}. Peel and mince @garlic{2%clove}.
Pick @sage{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; finely chop leaves.

Pat @scallops{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Transfer to a medium #bowl{};
toss with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon}, lemon zest, and ¼ of the garlic.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once water is boiling, add @butternut squash agnolotti{9%ounce} to pot; immediately
reduce to a low simmer. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente and floating
to the top, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings), then drain and set aside.

Heat pan with reserved bacon fat over high heat. Once pan is hot, add scallop
mixture in a single layer; cook, undisturbed, until browned and cooked through,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to low; add 1 tsp chopped sage (2 tsp for 4 servings) and 1 TBSP
@butter{3%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4). Cook, stirring, until butter has melted and
sage is fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a second medium bowl. Wipe out pan if necessary.

Let pan cool slightly; melt 1 TBSP butter (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in same pan over
medium heat. Cook, stirring, until butter is foamy and flecked with amber brown
bits, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in remaining garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{1} and @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, 1 TBSP
remaining chopped sage (2 TBSP for 4), and ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water (1/3
cup for 4). Bring to a simmer and cook until slightly thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.
Remove pan from heat.

Add @sour cream{2%tablespoon}, half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, and 1 TBSP
butter (2 TBSP for 4); stir until melted and smooth.

Gently stir in drained agnolotti, scallops, half the bacon, and a squeeze of
lemon juice; season with salt and pepper.

> If needed, stir in more pasta cooking water a splash at a time until pasta is
> coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide pasta between bowls; garnish with remaining Parmesan and remaining bacon.
Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.